1 Inventory Management Simulation

Let’s simulate the apple inventory management over a span of 52 weeks for FreshMart.

We will start by initializing our variables:

# Initial values
inventory <- 500
weeks <- 52
total_sales <- 0
total_orders <- 0
order_status <- FALSE
weeks_until_delivery <- 0

# Vectors to store weekly data
weekly_sales_vector <- numeric(weeks)
deliveries_received_vector <- numeric(weeks)
remaining_inventory_vector <- numeric(weeks)

Now, let’s run our simulation:

# Fix the seed
set.seed(123)

# Run the simulation
for (week in 1:weeks) {
  # Generate non-negative sales following a normal distribution
  weekly_sales <- max(0, round(rnorm(1, mean=100, sd=15)))
  
  # Check if demand exceeds available inventory
  weekly_sales <- min(weekly_sales, inventory)
  
  # Reduce inventory by weekly sales
  inventory <- inventory - weekly_sales
  total_sales <- total_sales + weekly_sales
  
  # Store weekly sales data
  weekly_sales_vector[week] <- weekly_sales
  
  # Check if order arrives
  if (order_status && weeks_until_delivery == 0) {
    inventory <- inventory + 300
    order_status <- FALSE
    deliveries_received_vector[week] <- 300
  } else if (order_status) {
    weeks_until_delivery <- weeks_until_delivery - 1
    deliveries_received_vector[week] <- 0
  } else {
    deliveries_received_vector[week] <- 0
  }
  
  # Check if new order should be placed
  if (inventory < 400 && !order_status) {
    order_status <- TRUE
    weeks_until_delivery <- 2
    total_orders <- total_orders + 1
  }
  
  # Store remaining inventory data
  remaining_inventory_vector[week] <- inventory
}

Finally, let’s present our annual report using the kable package:

annual_report <- tibble(
  Week = 1:weeks,
  `Apples Sold` = weekly_sales_vector,
  `Deliveries Received` = deliveries_received_vector,
  `Remaining Inventory` = remaining_inventory_vector
)

kable(annual_report, caption = "Annual Report for FreshMart's Apple Inventory", align = 'c')

# Remove duplicated
dat_bee_varroa <- dat_bee_varroa[!duplicated(dat_bee_varroa), ]
dat_bee_max <- dat_bee_max[!duplicated(dat_bee_max), ]

# Transform varroa from percentage to proportion

# Restore to long format
dat_bee_loss <- dat_bee_loss %>%

    names_to = "state",

  )

3 Hilbert matrix

  • 📝 Write a function named hilbert_matrix which computes a Hilbert matrix of dim_mat rows and dim_mat columns. Take dim_mat as a single positive integer argument using for loops. Run hilbert_matrix(10).
  • 🛠 Modify the function to print a console message before beginning the computation, issue a warning if a positive double is input, or raise an error if input is neither a positive double nor a positive integer. Test hilbert_matrix(10L), hilbert_matrix(10), hilbert_matrix("10").
  • 🧮 Based on an observation regarding the denominator trends in Hilbert matrix elements, propose a new implementation without for loops using rep and seq.
  • 🚀 Compare the execution performance of your solutions in the above steps.
  • Use profvis::profvis({...}) to profile each function, replacing ... with your code. Comment on the aspects of memory usage and computation time.
  • Use microbenchmark::microbenchmark({...}, {...}) for benchmarking, replacing ... with your implementations. Discuss the resulting outputs.

3.1 Solution with a loop

hilbert_matrix_loop <- function(dim_mat) {
    # Input validation
    if (!is.numeric(dim_mat) || dim_mat <= 0) {
        stop("Input must be a positive integer or double.")
    }
    
    # Computation
    mat <- matrix(NA_real_, nrow = dim_mat, ncol = dim_mat)
    
    for (i in 1:dim_mat) {
        for (j in 1:dim_mat) {
            mat[i, j] <- 1 / (i + j - 1)
        }
    }
    
    return(mat)
}

3.2 Solution without a slightly improved loop

hilbert_matrix_loop_faster <- function(dim_mat) {
    # Input validation
    if (!is.numeric(dim_mat) || dim_mat <= 0) {
        stop("Input must be a positive integer or double.")
    }
    
    # Computation
    mat <- matrix(NA_real_, nrow = dim_mat, ncol = dim_mat)
    
    for (i in 1:dim_mat) {
        mat[i, ] <- 1 / (i + 1:dim_mat - 1)
    }
    
    return(mat)
}

3.3 Solution using rep and seq

hilbert_matrix_seq <- function(dim_mat) {
    # Input validation
    if (!is.numeric(dim_mat) || dim_mat <= 0) {
        stop("Input must be a positive integer or double.")
    }
    
    # Computation
    x <- rep(seq_len(dim_mat), dim_mat) + rep(seq_len(dim_mat), each = dim_mat) - 1
    mat <- matrix(1 / x, nrow = dim_mat, ncol = dim_mat)
    
    return(mat)
}
